Aguita, </font><FONT face=Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular color=#191970 size=2> Officer of the <b>Silver Hawks</b></font><br><FONT face=Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular color=#191970 size=2>Mage of the 49th circle</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#A0B0E0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub29.ezboard.com/uquasimo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quasimo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>admin</span><br>  Posts: 481<br> <font color=#A0B0E0>(4/4/01 2:16:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub29.ezboard.com/fsilverhawksofdrinalfrm37.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Deep thoughts... (long)</span><hr size=1> Yes, it is about family and all that.. but to me.. I have a more 'black &amp; white' view of the reasons for dealing with loot the way we do.<br>
<br>
Now... really try hard here.. but imagine there is NO money in EQ.  <br>
<br>
If you think about EQ as a whole.. the whole server.. there are so many mobs up at one time that have so many &quot;items&quot;  be they swords, spells, or whatever.<br>
<br>
All of us can only make direct use of a fraction of everything.  One thing I always do when thinking about looting and how to be fair, yet effective, so we all benefit the most.  I always look at all of the limited resources.  Time and items.  <br>
<br>
Now, let me try to explain...<br>
<br>
Lets say there are 20 people and they each accumulate 10 items each over the course of a week.  All lottos were completely general with absolutely no regard for class, level, how much you've won, or anything.. if you where there you got to roll.  With this scenerio, of those 200 items, given there are 14 classes in EQ, lets say that each person is able to make good direct use 3 of his items (that's a high estimate I think).  That leaves 140 items in their banks or on alts.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm going to get to the factor of &quot;time&quot;.<br>
<br>
What do those 20 people do with those items?  Well... they end up selling or trading them.  Of course.. as everyone knows... this is not an easy task, as easy at it seems.  That's why merchandising is a long and old age business.  If it was so easy.. they wouldn't be making any money.  Eventually everyone gets what they want... of course.. if your merchanting, your not hunting.. and the amount of items (overall) goes down as a direct result.<br>
<br>
Now, with our loot rules.  Those 20 people produce 10 items each, yet every time.. the default rules where applied.  Everyone gained 6 (probably more) items that they could use... and 4 they could not.  <br>
<br>
Are they going to go sell them.. sure.. but what happened here?  The amount of items that are &quot;extra&quot; dropped from 140 to 80.  Now.. I estimated high on the bottom end, and low on the top end... I actually think it works out to be much much more.<br>
<br>
Anyhow... the end result:  People are out fighting instead of merchanting.  Getting even MORE stuff.  Sorry, but if I wanted to be a merchant.. I'd of had an ebay account long ago.<br>
<br>
I honestly believe Verant is really pretty smart.. here's why.  They made it so it just made absolutely NO sense in selling stuff to the vendor (everyone knows that), and it makes no sense in buying stuff from the vendor.... to encourage the trading.  Well, that's all  good.. the human interaction.. yet the side effect is all the WASTED time.<br>
<br>
Now.. some say my approach is &quot;socialistic&quot;.  Here is the truth however.  The ideoligy behind socialism is sound and is indeed more healty for the system (that being a group of people), however the implementation of it is where it goes wrong as we are dealing with humans... not farm animals.<br>
<br>
My approach takes into account the very beneficial effects of &quot;sharing the wealth&quot;.  In an evironment like EQ.. when the reality is you need 30 buddys to help you kill that dragon.. this approach makes the most sense (as long as they are your buddys).  This is why you belong to a guild.. this is why we are all family.<br>
<br>
Our loot rules however, do not 'force' anyone to do anything they don't want to do.  If you really don't like the class lotto system, hunt a different way, just make sure you communicate to everyone what the rules are.  We are all free to hunt with who we want, and do looting how you want.  However, don't go on a guild raid and complain because the only necromancer go the necro-only item.  Hope this helps some to understand why.<br>
